Purpose and Basic Usage  

useEffect is a React hook that runs side effects in function components. It executes after the component is rendered to the DOM.  
The function passed to useEffect runs when the component mounts and whenever any of its dependencies change.  
You can optionally return a cleanup function from the effect, which React will run when the component unmounts or before re-running the effect due to dependency changes.  
Example usage: setting up an interval timer and cleaning it up on unmount.

import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

function Timer() {
  const [seconds, setSeconds] = useState(0);

  useEffect(() => {
    const interval = setInterval(() => {
      setSeconds((s) => s + 1);
    }, 1000);
    return () => clearInterval(interval); // Cleanup
  }, []);

  return <p>Seconds: {seconds}</p>;
}

This effect runs once on mount (empty dependency array) and cleans up on unmount.1

Dependencies Array  

The second argument to useEffect is an array of dependencies. The effect runs again only if one of these dependencies changes.  
If the array is empty ([]), the effect runs only once after the initial render.  
Specifying dependencies correctly is important to avoid unnecessary or missing effect executions.1


Common Use Cases  

Data fetching on component mount.  
Setting up subscriptions or event listeners with proper cleanup.  
Running side effects in response to state or prop changes.1


Important Notes  

useEffect runs only on the client side, not during server-side rendering.  
Cleanup functions help prevent memory leaks by removing timers, subscriptions, or event listeners when the component unmounts or before the effect re-runs.  
Proper dependency management is crucial to avoid bugs or performance issues.1



In summary, useEffect is the primary React hook for managing side effects in function components, replacing lifecycle methods like componentDidMount, componentDidUpdate, and componentWillUnmount in class components. It enables declarative, clean, and efficient handling of effects with dependency tracking and cleanup support.
